a:260:{i:0;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391201112660723627";}i:1;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEvQL4qqUer";}i:2;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599273407;}i:3;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:1464:"Omega-3 fatty acids are important fats that provide many health benefits.â£
â£
Studies have found that they may reduce inflammation, decrease blood triglycerides and even reduce the risk of dementia.â£
â£
Of the three main types of omega-3 fatty acids, plant foods typically only contain alpha-linolenic acid (ALA).â£
â£
ALA is not as active in the body and must be converted to two other forms of omega-3 fatty acids â€” eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) â€” to bestow the same health benefits.â£
â£
Unfortunately, your bodyâ€™s ability to convert ALA is limited. Only about 5% of ALA is converted to EPA, while less than 0.5% is converted to DHA.â£
â£
Thus, if you donâ€™t supplement with algae oil (high in EPA and DHA) itâ€™s important to eat a good amount of ALA-rich foods to meet your omega-3 needs.â£
â£
Additionally, keep in mind your omega-6 to omega-3 ratio, as a diet low in omega-3s but high in omega-6s can increase inflammation and your risk of disease.
